1

00:00:04,310  -->  00:00:07,950
You saw how violin plots can be used to depict

2

00:00:07,950  -->  00:00:12,535
the relationship between a quantitative variable and a qualitative variable.

3

00:00:12,535  -->  00:00:16,985
An alternative plot that you might want to use, is the box plot.

4

00:00:16,985  -->  00:00:20,705
In a box plot, we compute descriptive statistics within

5

00:00:20,705  -->  00:00:24,965
each level and depict them graphically using a box and whiskers.

6

00:00:24,965  -->  00:00:28,470
The central line and each box indicates the median of

7

00:00:28,470  -->  00:00:33,730
the data and the upper and lower edges show the first and third quartiles.

8

00:00:33,730  -->  00:00:36,700
Whiskers are extended from the top and bottom of

9

00:00:36,700  -->  00:00:41,015
the boxes to indicate the largest and smallest values.

10

00:00:41,015  -->  00:00:46,680
25 percent of the data falls between each set of horizontal lines.

11

00:00:46,840  -->  00:00:53,030
Box plots often have outliers plotted as points beyond the ends of the whiskers.

12

00:00:53,030  -->  00:00:56,410
The most common upper bound on the length of the whiskers is

13

00:00:56,410  -->  00:01:00,515
1.5 times the interquartile range or box length.

14

00:01:00,515  -->  00:01:02,810
For the scores posted by North,

15

00:01:02,810  -->  00:01:08,600
the IQR is 5.5 and the maximum whisker length is 8.25.

16

00:01:08,600  -->  00:01:11,675
If we have outliers that are further than this distance

17

00:01:11,675  -->  00:01:14,920
above the top of the box are below the bottom of the box,

18

00:01:14,920  -->  00:01:18,890
they are depicted as single points and the whiskers are only extended

19

00:01:18,890  -->  00:01:22,985
to the farthest point within the 1.5 times IQR range.

20

00:01:22,985  -->  00:01:28,215
In this case, the maximum bound for the upper whisker is 66.75,

21

00:01:28,215  -->  00:01:31,270
so the maximum value of 68 is depicted as

22

00:01:31,270  -->  00:01:36,650
an outlier and the whisker is placed at the next largest value of 63.

23

00:01:36,650  -->  00:01:40,300
While box plots do a fine job of summarizing the data,

24

00:01:40,300  -->  00:01:43,940
there are some distributional details that can get lost.

25

00:01:43,940  -->  00:01:47,360
For example, the box plot reveals more clearly than

26

00:01:47,360  -->  00:01:49,580
the violin plot that the North team had

27

00:01:49,580  -->  00:01:52,800
the worst performance and the Central team the best.

28

00:01:52,800  -->  00:01:55,950
However, it is not obvious from the box plot that

29

00:01:55,950  -->  00:02:01,385
the South team scores include a broad plateaus between about 60 and 62 points,

30

00:02:01,385  -->  00:02:03,880
as you can see in the violin plot.

31

00:02:03,880  -->  00:02:08,220
One alternative approach for showing summary statistics is to start with

32

00:02:08,220  -->  00:02:13,355
a violin plot and then add lines to the curves to denote quartile points.

33

00:02:13,355  -->  00:02:16,975
However, this is a bit less direct than the box plot.

34

00:02:16,975  -->  00:02:20,020
So, when it comes to explanatory data visualization,

35

00:02:20,020  -->  00:02:24,480
you might want to choose a box plot for simplicity and focus.
